<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: CHULA VISTA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chula Vista Mayor-elect Gayle McCandliss said Friday that she will take the 
oath of office Tuesday night despite suffering from a liver illness that has 
forced her to undergo chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
McCandliss, who formerly served as a councilwoman, said she went public with 
her illness to dispel "a lot of questions and suppositions about my health." 
</P>
<P>
She said a cancerous tumor was removed from her colon July 31, and cells from 
the tumor had traveled to the liver. 
</P>
<P>
However, McCandliss denied rumors that she is suffering from cancer of the 
liver. 
</P>
<P>
"It is not liver cancer," she said. "I (am) feeling well. My liver functions 
are normal. I am feeling good. . . . The cells traveled to a secondary site, 
that's all." 
</P>
<P>
She acknowledged that the last few months have been a "difficult battle," but 
expressed optimism that she will be able to handle all mayoral duties. 
</P>
<P>
McCandliss will replace Mayor Greg Cox, who is stepping down after nine years 
as Chula Vista's first full-time mayor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
