<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: BOXING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A member of the New Mexico Athletic Commission said he was unaware that 
super-flyweight champion Johnny Tapia had to take a drug test after a title 
fight in Albuquerque. Tapia, 23, tested positive for cocaine Nov. 14, nearly 
three weeks after he retained his U.S. Boxing Assn. title Oct. 26 against 
Santiago Caballero of Venezuela, New Mexico authorities said. The test was 
taken after Max Abeyta, events coordinator and chief deputy inspector for the 
New Mexico Athletic Commission, discovered during a routine check about a week 
after the fight that neither fighter had been tested. 
</P>
