<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISCREDITED MILLI VANILLI STILL ON 1990 GRAMMY BALLOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
And the winner of the 1990 Grammy is . . . Milli Vanilli? 
</P>
<P>
That Grammy nightmare could become reality -- sort of -- when the music 
industry awards are handed out in New York on Feb. 20. Though the lip-sync duo 
was stripped of it's best new artist Grammy from last year, Milli Vanilli 
appears in four categories on the first-round ballot that went out this week to 
the 6,000 voting members of the National Academy of Recording Arts &amp; 
Sciences. The duo is listed for album of the year, record of the year, pop 
performance by group or duo and song of the year. 
</P>
<P>
The ballots, which will be used to select actual nominees for the 1990 Grammy 
awards, were printed and readied for mailing before the lip-syncing story 
broke. 
</P>
<P>
Academy president Michael Greene said Friday that votes in the first three 
categories would not be counted. 
</P>
<P>
"The same factors that rendered them ineligible for the award last year renders 
them ineligible this year," Greene said. 
</P>
<P>
But Milli Vanilli's "Blame It on the Rain" is making it into the song of the 
year category. Though the song category honors the writers -- in this case pop 
songsmith Dianne Warren -- and not the performers, it could be a huge 
embarrassment to the academy to even tangentially honor former Milli frontmen 
Rob Pilatus and Fabrice Morvan. 
</P>
<P>
But Greene said that as far as he knows there is no reason to remove the 
group's work from the song category, though the matter will be decided 
officially at a meeting of the academy's awards and nominations committee on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Greene said that no letter will be sent to Grammy voters to make them aware of 
the ineligibility but that a reminder of it might be included in regular 
communications concerning the voting updates. 
</P>
<P>
But the pair themselves find the appearance on the ballot "amusing," according 
to their manager, Carsten Heyn. 
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate the mention on the ballot," Heyn said, after speaking to Pilatus 
and Morvan, who are trying to launch a singing career of their own. "And we 
hope that Robby and Fabrice will win a real Grammy in the future in order to 
give back to the fans what they deserve." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, GRAMMY GAFFE: Milli Vanilli was stripped of its 1989 Grammy but the 
lip-syncing duo appears in four categories on the preliminary ballot just 
mailed to 6,000 voters. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
MILLI VANILLI (MUSIC GROUP); GRAMMY AWARDS; VOTING; NATIONAL ACADEMY OF 
RECORDING ARTS &amp; SCIENCES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
