<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; 
</P>
<P>
KWIZ RADIO DEALS WITH COMPLAINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY HELEN BERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KWIZ radio, which had until today to solve interference problems caused by its 
antenna, has successfully addressed the complaints of residents and will 
continue to broadcast from a hillside in Orange. 
</P>
<P>
In August, the City Council ordered the station to deal with the complaints or 
risk losing the conditional use permit that allowed it to broadcast from the 
western slope of Crawford Hills. 
</P>
<P>
KWIZ, operated by Liberman Broadcasting, has broadcast adult contemporary music 
for years through the television sets, tape decks and telephones of area 
residents. 
</P>
<P>
The station spent hundreds of hours and thousands of dollars to resolve 
problems at 73 homes, according to station officials. The company hired 
engineers and other personnel to make more than 100 house calls to community 
members. 
</P>
<P>
Shirley Grindle, one of the residents who helped bring the problem to the 
council's attention, congratulated KWIZ for "taking the bull by the horns" and 
addressing the complaints. MARY HELEN BERG 
</P>
</TEXT>
